I Haue hitherto examined his • nswere to the 3. places which I alleadged in my Adioynder out of S. Augustine to proue that S. Peter bare the person of the Church in respect of his Primacy, and you haue seene how well Mayster Collins hath quit himselfe in the answere therof;
it resteth now that I say somewhat to that which followeth immediatly in M. Coll. touching the place of S. Aug. which was first in question betwixt my Lord of Winchester and me, & hath been the cause of all this dispute. And for as much as I charged his LP. with the lame quotation of the sayd place (in respect that the precedent, & subsequent wordes in S.
• ugustine left out by his LP. did shew that the place doth make rather for the primacy of S Peter then agaynst it) M. Collins being desirous to pay me with my own money, chargeth me roūdly with the lame quotation also of the sayd place, which remayneth to be discussed, and debated betwixt vs.

29. I omit certaine other impertinent fooleryes of his, not worth the mentioning, and much lesse the answering. To come to his Achilles, I meane to his argument,
which he thinketh doth ouerthrow vs horse and foote, and therefore he bids me arrige aures Pamphile; albeit insteed thereof, he might haue done well to haue made vse of his Epphata, to open my eares; but I hope to stop his mouth with Obmutesce. Wel then you shal heare his whole discourse; thus he sayth pag. 393. lin. 7. Yet let vs goe on with Epiphanius, a step further, Coluerunt enim & adorauerunt creaturam praeter Creatorem &c. It is a trespasse with Epiphanius, to worship the creature, or to adore the creature (for he puts both) praeter Creatorem, besydes the Creatour, that is, though you exclude not the worship of the Creatour, but only take in the worship of the creature: si enim Angelos adorari non vult, quanto magis eam quae genita est ab Anna? &c. non tamen aliter genita est praeter hominum naturam; sed sicut omnes ex semine viri, & vtero mulieris. Heere, heer, arrige aures Pamphile, heer you should do wel to list a whyle, you Poliphilus, or rather Pamphilus, of all bastard Deityes. For if, sayth he, God will not haue the Angells worshiped, how much more will not be haue her which was borne of Anna, & yet not borne otherways, then the fashion is, and nature of all mankynd; but &c. Two great poynts assoyled by Epiphanius in these few words;
one, that the Virgin Mary, was not conceiued nor borne after extraordinary manner, as the Iesuits affirme, but euen as others are, which must needs be in sinne, and corruption. Another, that she is not so exalted in heauen, but inferiour to Angells, or els the consequence were not good; if not Angells much lesse Mary the daughtes of Anne. Thus hath Collyns spit out his spyte against the blessed Virgin to impugne her immaculate purity, & the transcendent degree of glory which she worthily possesseth in heauen.
